Castor oil and ricinoleic acid are both liquid at room temperature and their boiling points are 313 and 412 °C, respectively, making them good capping materials to be used in place of air-sensitive, toxic, and inexpensive chemicals or solvents. Castor oil and ricinoleic acid-capped PbS nanocrystals were synthesized via a solution-based thermolysis using lead acetate salt and elemental sulfur as lead and sulfur precursors. The isolated solid product dispersed in castor oil or ricinoleic acid was rapidly injected into a 6.0 g castor oil or ricinoleic acid pre-heated at 280 °C. The mixture was thermolyzed for 2 h under stirring, with aliquots taken out from the reaction mixture after ½, 1, and 2 h time intervals. Excess anhydrous methanol was immediately added to the centrifuging tubes to isolate or precipitate the PbS nanocrystals. The sequence of reactions is shown below:2S(s)+NaBH4(s)+7H2O(l)→2NaHS(aq)+Na2B4O7(aq)+14H2(g),NaHS(aq)+PbCl2(aq)→PbS(s)+NaCl(aq)+HCl(aq).\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
